1
00:00:42,509 --> 00:00:45,115
(indistinct chattering)

2
00:00:47,881 --> 00:00:50,293
Man: I'm not very interested
in my school days

3
00:00:50,350 --> 00:00:54,355
and feel no special
nostalgia for them.

4
00:00:54,421 --> 00:00:56,594
But I remember Sixth Form.

5
00:01:01,027 --> 00:01:03,166
Good morning.

6
00:01:03,229 --> 00:01:05,140
And welcome to you all

7
00:01:05,198 --> 00:01:07,542
as we begin the new term.

8
00:01:08,768 --> 00:01:10,679
Man: In those days,
we imagined ourselves

9
00:01:10,737 --> 00:01:12,546
as being in a holding pen,

10
00:01:12,605 --> 00:01:14,881
waiting to be released
into our lives.

11
00:01:14,941 --> 00:01:16,978
Headmaster:
From summer to autumn.

12
00:01:17,043 --> 00:01:18,784
So, too, do we think ahead...

13
00:01:18,845 --> 00:01:21,086
(chuckles)
Rather him than us.

14
00:01:22,515 --> 00:01:24,188
Man:
And when that moment would come,

15
00:01:24,250 --> 00:01:26,059
we would be at university.

16
00:01:26,119 --> 00:01:28,258
(upbeat music playing)

17
00:01:28,321 --> 00:01:30,426
(indistinct chattering)

18
00:01:32,125 --> 00:01:36,335
How were we to know that
our lives had already begun,

19
00:01:36,396 --> 00:01:40,435
and our release would only be
into a larger holding pen?

20
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:43,674
And in time,
a larger holding pen.

21
00:01:47,841 --> 00:01:50,117
When you are young,
you want your emotions

22
00:01:50,176 --> 00:01:53,123
to be like the ones
you read about in books.

23
00:01:54,781 --> 00:01:57,159
You want them
to overturn your life

24
00:01:57,217 --> 00:01:59,254
and create a new reality.

25
00:01:59,319 --> 00:02:00,963
- (alarm clock ringing)
- But as that second hand

26
00:02:00,987 --> 00:02:04,457
insists on speeding up
and time delivers us all too quickly

27
00:02:04,524 --> 00:02:07,437
into middle age,
and then old age,

28
00:02:07,494 --> 00:02:11,067
that's when you want something
a little milder, don't you?

29
00:02:13,666 --> 00:02:16,010
You want your emotions
to support your life

30
00:02:16,069 --> 00:02:17,605
as it has become.

31
00:02:19,472 --> 00:02:23,215
You want them to tell you
that everything is going to be okay.

32
00:02:24,911 --> 00:02:26,948
And is there anything
wrong with that?

33
00:02:30,350 --> 00:02:32,352
(classical music playing)

34
00:02:44,797 --> 00:02:47,539
"Sir, according to
your recent survey,

35
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:49,773
95% of British motorists

36
00:02:49,836 --> 00:02:52,908
describe themselves
as 'above average' drivers.

37
00:02:52,972 --> 00:02:55,248
But by the law of averages,

38
00:02:55,308 --> 00:02:57,413
we are, most of us,
bound to be average.

39
00:02:57,477 --> 00:02:58,649
Are we not?

40
00:02:58,711 --> 00:03:01,248
Anthony Webster, London.“

41
00:03:14,127 --> 00:03:16,073
(exhales deeply)
Good timing.

42
00:03:16,129 --> 00:03:18,541
Sorry?
(sighs)

43
00:03:19,299 --> 00:03:20,642
(device beeping)

44
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:24,739
Oh, uh, sign there, thanks.

45
00:03:24,804 --> 00:03:28,342
- Lovely morning, isn't it?
- Hmm.

46
00:03:28,408 --> 00:03:29,785
- (device beeps)
- Thank you.

47
00:03:37,984 --> 00:03:39,986
(music playing)

48
00:04:50,590 --> 00:04:52,399
(knocks on door)

49
00:05:02,201 --> 00:05:04,772
- Can I help you?
- Just looking.

50
00:05:04,837 --> 00:05:08,080
- By all means.
- Oh! Wow.

51
00:05:09,309 --> 00:05:11,050
These are beautiful.

52
00:05:12,612 --> 00:05:14,148
How much is this one?

53
00:05:15,782 --> 00:05:17,989
£2,399.

54
00:05:18,051 --> 00:05:19,428
£2,000?

55
00:05:19,485 --> 00:05:20,793
Extremely rare model.

56
00:05:20,853 --> 00:05:23,891
- Still works, huh?
- Of course.

57
00:05:23,956 --> 00:05:25,663
How do you source them
on the Internet?

58
00:05:25,725 --> 00:05:27,727
I've been in the Leica business
for some time,

59
00:05:27,794 --> 00:05:29,899
so we have our own
exclusive sources.

60
00:05:29,962 --> 00:05:32,966
"We"?
It's just you, isn't it?

61
00:05:33,032 --> 00:05:34,743
If there's anything
you're particularly interested in,

62
00:05:34,767 --> 00:05:37,111
I may be able to help you.

63
00:05:37,170 --> 00:05:38,979
Do you have anything cheaper?

64
00:05:40,406 --> 00:05:42,443
Some Leica Ills, 500.

65
00:05:42,508 --> 00:05:43,851
500?

66
00:05:44,410 --> 00:05:45,980
Wow.

67
00:05:46,045 --> 00:05:48,150
These are the finest
cameras ever made.

68
00:05:48,214 --> 00:05:50,660
People buy them
because they love them.

69
00:05:51,317 --> 00:05:53,024
Well, as they say,

70
00:05:53,086 --> 00:05:55,032
I'd be rich
if I didn't have kids.

71
00:05:56,556 --> 00:05:58,194
You got kids?

72
00:05:58,257 --> 00:06:01,170
- Excuse me?
- I've got two baby girls.

73
00:06:04,097 --> 00:06:07,044
- I have a daughter.
- Oh.

74
00:06:07,100 --> 00:06:10,343
Fathers and daughters, eh?
Very special.

75
00:06:18,311 --> 00:06:19,483
Okay.

76
00:06:19,545 --> 00:06:20,546
(inhales sharply)

77
00:06:20,613 --> 00:06:24,584
Well, I'll look you up
when the kids have left home.

78
00:06:24,650 --> 00:06:26,129
Tony Webster.

79
00:06:26,185 --> 00:06:29,098
- Have a lovely day, Tony Webster.
- Okay.

80
00:06:32,959 --> 00:06:34,905
(cell phone chiming)

81
00:06:43,469 --> 00:06:44,573
(cell phone beeps)

82
00:06:44,637 --> 00:06:47,174
- Hello, Margaret.
- I'm calling to remind you that

83
00:06:47,240 --> 00:06:49,811
this evening you're duty bound
to attend the NCT

84
00:06:49,876 --> 00:06:51,719
with your beloved daughter.

85
00:06:51,778 --> 00:06:53,052
Tonight?

86
00:06:53,112 --> 00:06:55,524
Uh, oh, no, no, no, sorry.
No can do.

87
00:06:55,581 --> 00:06:58,585
Oh, for God's sake.
This should be in your diary.

88
00:06:58,651 --> 00:06:59,686
Susie's relying on you.

89
00:06:59,752 --> 00:07:03,290
You know I can'! Do it
with this thing on my leg.

90
00:07:03,356 --> 00:07:05,097
I'm winding you up.
(laughs)

91
00:07:05,158 --> 00:07:07,502
Somebody's in a playful mood.

92
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:08,800
Always.

93
00:07:08,861 --> 00:07:11,967
Well, don't forget to dig out
something loose-fitting.

94
00:07:12,031 --> 00:07:14,238
Lycra. All-in-one.

95
00:07:15,635 --> 00:07:17,546
Very attractive.

96
00:07:17,603 --> 00:07:19,241
What are you doing this evening?

97
00:07:20,273 --> 00:07:22,253
Working. What else?

98
00:07:22,308 --> 00:07:24,083
Really?

99
00:07:24,143 --> 00:07:26,714
So I'm expecting a full report
in the morning.

100
00:07:26,779 --> 00:07:29,555
- How's the foot, by the way?
- Bye, Tony.

101
00:07:29,615 --> 00:07:32,926
- (call disconnects)
- Hmm, charming.

102
00:07:33,419 --> 00:07:35,092
(cell phone beeps)

103
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:11,526
- (car lock beeps)
- (intercom buzzes)

104
00:08:13,259 --> 00:08:15,569
- Woman: Hi.
- It's me.

105
00:08:15,628 --> 00:08:16,732
You're not Mum.

106
00:08:16,796 --> 00:08:19,276
Indeed, I'm not.
Your mother sent me.

107
00:08:19,332 --> 00:08:22,506
I'm your geriatric knight
in shining armor.

108
00:08:22,568 --> 00:08:25,174
- Can you give me a minute?
- Can I come in?

109
00:08:26,772 --> 00:08:29,514
- (door buzzes)
- Thank you.

110
00:08:32,278 --> 00:08:34,857
Man on radio: The Prime Minister
has insisted Britain will be safer

111
00:08:34,881 --> 00:08:38,522
and economically stronger
if it remains in the European Union.

112
00:08:38,584 --> 00:08:41,064
He said a vote to leave
would cause such instability

113
00:08:41,120 --> 00:08:42,599
on the financial markets

114
00:08:42,655 --> 00:08:45,829
that the UK could be
tipped back into recession.

115
00:08:45,892 --> 00:08:47,769
(turns off radio)

116
00:08:47,827 --> 00:08:51,639
- All right, Dad, let's do this.
- Have you seen this?

117
00:08:51,697 --> 00:08:53,301
I know, I know.

118
00:08:53,366 --> 00:08:54,902
It's the bollocking upstairs neighbor.

119
00:08:54,967 --> 00:08:57,072
- What happened?
- I don't know.

120
00:08:57,136 --> 00:08:58,444
Overflowing bath or something.

121
00:08:58,504 --> 00:09:01,451
- That's ridiculous.
- I know.

122
00:09:01,507 --> 00:09:03,145
Come on.

123
00:09:03,209 --> 00:09:04,916
I'll write to them.

124
00:09:05,745 --> 00:09:08,351
Dad, no one writes letters anymore.

125
00:09:15,187 --> 00:09:18,999
So, I should probably warn you,
tonight will likely feature lesbians.

126
00:09:19,058 --> 00:09:20,162
(Tony laughs)

127
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:22,763
I've known quite a number
of lesbians in my time,

128
00:09:22,828 --> 00:09:24,171
thank you very much.

129
00:09:24,230 --> 00:09:26,039
Artificially inseminated lesbians.

130
00:09:26,098 --> 00:09:30,274
(laughs) I once knew
a pasteurized lesbian.

131
00:09:30,336 --> 00:09:34,716
Just try not to say anything
too mental, will you?

132
00:09:34,774 --> 00:09:36,913
The woman who runs the group
takes the whole thing

133
00:09:36,976 --> 00:09:39,252
- pretty seriously.
- (sarcastic laugh)

134
00:09:39,312 --> 00:09:41,553
I'm sure she does.

135
00:09:43,683 --> 00:09:44,718
(Susie sighs)

136
00:09:44,784 --> 00:09:48,095
Hi, I'm Tony.
I'm this evening's stand-in mother.

137
00:09:48,154 --> 00:09:49,398
Standing in for
the mother of the mother.

138
00:09:49,422 --> 00:09:52,767
You just rock with it.
And you will get a rhythm.

139
00:09:52,825 --> 00:09:55,738
But, uh, not to worry.
I have been effectively sterilized.

140
00:09:55,795 --> 00:09:57,672
But the voice
of experience tonight.

141
00:09:57,730 --> 00:09:59,835
Now the contraction comes.

142
00:09:59,899 --> 00:10:01,936
So... sit up.

143
00:10:02,001 --> 00:10:03,571
Your contraction's coming.

144
00:10:03,636 --> 00:10:07,106
Hi, I'm Susie.
Uh, this is my first.

145
00:10:07,173 --> 00:10:11,087
Um, I'm expecting a boy in October.

146
00:10:11,143 --> 00:10:14,681
Instructor:
You're in the arms of your protector

147
00:10:14,747 --> 00:10:16,988
and your baby,
it is going to be fine.

148
00:10:17,049 --> 00:10:19,290
And I think I'm gonna
name him Joshua.

149
00:10:19,352 --> 00:10:21,389
- Instructor: Oh!
- Really?

150
00:10:21,454 --> 00:10:22,455
Yeah.

151
00:10:22,521 --> 00:10:25,900
Instructor:
We've got another surge that has started.

152
00:10:25,958 --> 00:10:27,767
- (bone cracks)
- So...

153
00:10:27,827 --> 00:10:30,330
You okay there, Dad?

154
00:10:30,396 --> 00:10:33,570
So maybe if you come further down.

155
00:10:35,401 --> 00:10:37,142
That's it.

156
00:10:37,203 --> 00:10:38,409
See, this is the other thing.

157
00:10:38,471 --> 00:10:40,781
Depends if your partner's agile
or not agile,

158
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:43,286
you know,
or to get into positions.

159
00:10:43,342 --> 00:10:45,982
It's taking them
into consideration as well

160
00:10:46,045 --> 00:10:48,085
and make whatever's comfortable
for the both of you.

161
00:10:48,147 --> 00:10:50,559
(indistinct conversations)

162
00:10:55,988 --> 00:10:57,695
- Me, as well.
- Yes.

163
00:10:57,757 --> 00:11:00,704
It was amazing.
And so much fun.

164
00:11:13,606 --> 00:11:16,883
Wait here a sec.
I wanna give you something.

165
00:11:16,942 --> 00:11:18,580
Oh, all right.

166
00:11:20,279 --> 00:11:21,724
Susie:
Oh. (Chuckles)

167
00:11:24,116 --> 00:11:25,288
(sighs)

168
00:11:27,753 --> 00:11:29,926
Man on radio: There has,
and continues to be criticism

169
00:11:29,989 --> 00:11:33,266
of the government's approach
to rebuilding Britain's economy.

170
00:11:33,325 --> 00:11:35,134
And we're better placed
to withstand

171
00:11:35,194 --> 00:11:37,765
an ideological drive
to shrink the state,

172
00:11:37,830 --> 00:11:41,141
with some of the most vulnerable people
in society paying the price.

173
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:43,278
Woman on radio: A charge that
the ministers would of course, reject?

174
00:11:43,302 --> 00:11:46,010
Man on radio: Yeah, sure,
they'd insist the tough measures

175
00:11:46,072 --> 00:11:49,144
they're taking will ensure Britain's
finances get back onto an even keel.

176
00:11:49,208 --> 00:11:52,087
And we're better placed to
withstand any economic shocks

177
00:11:52,144 --> 00:11:53,488
that may come our way
in the future.

178
00:11:53,512 --> 00:11:56,755
Woman on radio:
Economic shocks such as, for instance...

179
00:11:56,816 --> 00:11:59,490
(frying pan sizzling)

180
00:11:59,552 --> 00:12:01,031
(hissing)

181
00:12:02,121 --> 00:12:03,828
Whoops.
(laughs)

182
00:12:09,161 --> 00:12:10,936
- Susie: Here.
- What's this?

183
00:12:10,996 --> 00:12:13,408
Time to join the 21 st century.

184
00:12:13,466 --> 00:12:16,470
Not least because I'm about to burst
and Mum's an invalid.

185
00:12:16,535 --> 00:12:19,311
- You're my only hope.
- (laughs)

186
00:12:19,371 --> 00:12:21,282
- Bye, Dad.
- Bye.

187
00:12:26,112 --> 00:12:27,489
(engine starts)

188
00:12:31,517 --> 00:12:34,396
(indistinct chatter on radio)

189
00:12:44,263 --> 00:12:46,265
(music playing)

190
00:12:53,739 --> 00:12:56,515
(knuckles cracking)

191
00:12:56,575 --> 00:12:58,646
(printer whirring)

192
00:13:03,349 --> 00:13:04,657
(computer chimes)

193
00:13:07,386 --> 00:13:09,696
(printer scanning)

194
00:13:27,473 --> 00:13:29,475
(clock dings, ticking)

195
00:13:45,524 --> 00:13:49,233
(man whistling)

196
00:13:49,295 --> 00:13:51,832
(rattling)

197
00:13:56,802 --> 00:13:58,145
Oh, good morning.

198
00:13:58,204 --> 00:14:00,047
Just about.

199
00:14:00,105 --> 00:14:03,746
Um... right.
Let me get that...

200
00:14:03,809 --> 00:14:06,551
- 82...
- (device beeping)

201
00:14:07,179 --> 00:14:09,181
Uh, and then you need to...

202
00:14:09,248 --> 00:14:12,354
No. Oh, sorry. There.

203
00:14:14,520 --> 00:14:16,522
- Right.
- Thanks.

204
00:14:17,489 --> 00:14:19,628
All right.
Have a nice...

205
00:14:37,276 --> 00:14:41,418
Woman: "Dear, Tony, I think it right
that you should have the attached.

206
00:14:42,514 --> 00:14:46,189
Adrian always
spoke warmly of you,

207
00:14:46,252 --> 00:14:49,825
and perhaps you'll find it
an interesting, if painful,

208
00:14:49,889 --> 00:14:52,836
memento of long ago.

209
00:14:54,760 --> 00:14:56,933
I am also leaving you
some money.

210
00:14:56,996 --> 00:14:58,703
You may find this a bit strange,

211
00:14:58,764 --> 00:15:01,404
and, to tell you the truth,
I'm not entirely sure

212
00:15:01,467 --> 00:15:03,071
what my own motives are,

213
00:15:03,135 --> 00:15:07,083
but I wish you well,
even from beyond the grave.

214
00:15:07,139 --> 00:15:09,380
Yours, Sarah Ford.

215
00:15:09,441 --> 00:15:11,512
P.S., it may sound a little odd,

216
00:15:11,577 --> 00:15:14,524
but I think the last months
of his life were happy.“

217
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,059
Woman:
Mr. Webster?

218
00:15:16,115 --> 00:15:20,586
"Dear, Tony, I think it right
you should have the attached.

219
00:15:20,653 --> 00:15:22,462
Adrian always
spoke warmly of you,

220
00:15:22,521 --> 00:15:24,721
and perhaps you will find it
an interesting, if painful,

221
00:15:24,757 --> 00:15:27,533
- memento of long ago."
- We do not currently...

222
00:15:27,593 --> 00:15:31,439
So it is this attached item referred to,
which is the missing item.

223
00:15:31,497 --> 00:15:34,876
We do not currently have
the second item in our possession.

224
00:15:35,634 --> 00:15:37,272
Excuse me?

225
00:15:37,336 --> 00:15:39,976
I said, we do not currently have
the second item in our possession.

226
00:15:40,639 --> 00:15:42,641
Well, where on earth is it?

227
00:15:42,708 --> 00:15:45,018
The item is currently
with Mrs. Ford's executor.

228
00:15:45,077 --> 00:15:46,181
Mrs. Ford's daughter.

229
00:15:46,245 --> 00:15:49,055
- Veronica?
- Mm.

230
00:15:49,114 --> 00:15:51,685
- You've asked for it, I assume?
- That's correct.

231
00:15:52,985 --> 00:15:55,192
Has she given any reason
for withholding it?

232
00:15:55,254 --> 00:15:56,699
I'm afraid I don't know.

233
00:15:56,755 --> 00:15:59,395
Forgive me,
but what do you know?

234
00:15:59,458 --> 00:16:01,438
What is it?
Have you actually seen it?

235
00:16:01,493 --> 00:16:04,633
No, I haven't. Um...

236
00:16:04,697 --> 00:16:06,734
I can look it up for you,
if you wish.

237
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:08,710
Please do.

238
00:16:10,135 --> 00:16:12,137
(keyboard clacking)

239
00:16:13,205 --> 00:16:17,085
So, Mrs. Ford's will
describes the second item...

240
00:16:19,345 --> 00:16:21,518
- as a diary.
- A diary?

241
00:16:21,580 --> 00:16:23,389
Belonging to Mrs. Ford?

242
00:16:23,449 --> 00:16:24,860
I'm afraid that's not clear.

243
00:16:26,852 --> 00:16:29,924
Can you let me have
Veronica's address, please?

244
00:16:29,989 --> 00:16:33,698
I'm sorry, we can't give out clients'
addresses without their permission.

245
00:16:33,759 --> 00:16:35,238
Veronica and I know one another.

246
00:16:35,294 --> 00:16:38,070
Well, did know one another,
albeit rather a long time ago.

247
00:16:38,130 --> 00:16:41,339
I'm afraid I would need
her authority to do that.

248
00:16:42,301 --> 00:16:45,908
Well, will you kindly request
that authority, please?

249
00:16:45,971 --> 00:16:47,075
Very well.

250
00:16:47,139 --> 00:16:50,211
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

251
00:16:50,275 --> 00:16:52,881
It was a pleasure meeting you,
Mr. Webster.

252
00:16:52,945 --> 00:16:54,856
Good-bye.

253
00:16:54,913 --> 00:16:57,723
And you should know
that my ex-wife is a QC.

254
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:03,022
- (indistinct chattering)
- (music playing)

255
00:17:05,357 --> 00:17:07,064
Yeah, this all seems fine.

256
00:17:07,126 --> 00:17:10,403
So, she has it, the diary.
That much at least we do know.

257
00:17:10,462 --> 00:17:12,567
Sorry, who has it?

258
00:17:12,631 --> 00:17:14,872
You know, those things
are really bad for you.

259
00:17:14,933 --> 00:17:17,379
They just build up excess mucus.

260
00:17:17,436 --> 00:17:19,746
I'm sorry, Dr. Webster,

261
00:17:19,805 --> 00:17:22,083
didn't think we were here
to discuss my bread-stick intake.

262
00:17:22,107 --> 00:17:23,814
All right, sorry, sorry, sorry.

263
00:17:25,177 --> 00:17:26,850
Feel better once we've eaten.

264
00:17:28,113 --> 00:17:29,615
Once we've ordered. Ah.

265
00:17:29,681 --> 00:17:31,991
Thank God.

266
00:17:33,352 --> 00:17:36,959
- Sir, Madam?
- I'd like the Carbonara, please.

267
00:17:37,022 --> 00:17:40,265
Mm, <i>Penne Con Salsa
Di Pomodoro E Basilico.</i>

268
00:17:43,529 --> 00:17:44,530
Thank you.

269
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:56,116
- What?
- Tell me, tell me.

270
00:17:56,175 --> 00:17:58,177
(rock music playing)

271
00:18:07,820 --> 00:18:10,926
<i>♪ I feel depressed, I feel so bad ♪</i>

272
00:18:13,659 --> 00:18:16,765
<i>♪ 'Cause you're the best girl
that I've ever had ♪</i>

273
00:18:19,398 --> 00:18:23,073
<i>♪ I can't get your love,
I can't get affection ♪</i>

274
00:18:25,571 --> 00:18:28,848
<i>♪ Oh, little girl,
psychotic reaction ♪</i>

275
00:18:29,741 --> 00:18:31,118
<i>♪ And it feels like this... ♪</i>

276
00:18:31,176 --> 00:18:32,849
(camera clicking)

277
00:18:47,626 --> 00:18:49,435
Not enjoying the party?

278
00:18:51,663 --> 00:18:53,734
It's not really my cup of tea.

279
00:18:56,835 --> 00:18:58,610
I'm a manic depressive, you see.

280
00:19:00,806 --> 00:19:02,217
Not another one.

281
00:19:04,176 --> 00:19:07,589
Clifton Suspension Bridge.
My mind's made up.

282
00:19:22,361 --> 00:19:23,965
Done.

283
00:19:24,029 --> 00:19:25,406
Mm.

284
00:19:25,464 --> 00:19:26,704
Well...

285
00:19:27,833 --> 00:19:28,971
it was nice to meet you.

286
00:19:36,542 --> 00:19:39,523
. TOW-
. TOW-

287
00:19:40,879 --> 00:19:44,827
<i>♪ Oh, little girl, would you like
to take a ride now? ♪</i>

288
00:19:46,785 --> 00:19:49,994
<i>♪ I can't get your love,
I can't get satisfaction ♪</i>

289
00:19:52,991 --> 00:19:55,938
<i>♪ Oh, little girl,
psychotic reaction ♪</i>

290
00:20:03,569 --> 00:20:05,776
(car passing)

291
00:20:11,243 --> 00:20:13,086
(horn honking)

292
00:20:14,780 --> 00:20:16,521
I wonder how far it is.

293
00:20:19,785 --> 00:20:22,925
It's 245 feet.

294
00:20:24,089 --> 00:20:26,194
So not very far, then.

295
00:20:29,127 --> 00:20:31,835
Why is your watch
on the inside of your wrist?

296
00:20:32,831 --> 00:20:35,004
Is it? I don't know.

297
00:20:43,475 --> 00:20:44,647
(camera clicks)

298
00:20:47,546 --> 00:20:49,184
So what's your subject, then?

299
00:20:51,516 --> 00:20:55,464
<i>- Le Frangais.</i>
- Oh. Oui.

300
00:20:55,520 --> 00:20:59,058
<i>- Parlez-vous Frangais?</i>
- Oui.

301
00:21:03,662 --> 00:21:04,834
(chuckles)

302
00:21:06,398 --> 00:21:07,672
(speaks French)

303
00:21:10,936 --> 00:21:12,108
(clears throat)

304
00:21:16,575 --> 00:21:18,213
<i>Magnifique.</i>

305
00:21:18,277 --> 00:21:23,022
<i>♪ There was a time
I thought of mine only... ♪</i>

306
00:21:25,050 --> 00:21:26,324
Cheers.

307
00:21:27,786 --> 00:21:29,060
Cheers.

308
00:21:31,723 --> 00:21:34,704
<i>♪ I was noble personage ♪</i>

309
00:21:34,760 --> 00:21:38,674
<i>♪ Born to beautify the page ♪</i>

310
00:21:39,731 --> 00:21:45,181
<i>♪ If I used time to set it down ♪</i>

311
00:21:49,941 --> 00:21:52,421
<i>♪ There was a time
I thought of mine... ♪</i>

312
00:21:52,477 --> 00:21:54,388
Tony: You still haven't
told me your name.

313
00:21:59,051 --> 00:22:02,430
I tend to find it inadvisable
to give out my name

314
00:22:02,487 --> 00:22:04,933
to strange men
I've only just met.

315
00:22:06,858 --> 00:22:08,838
Margaret: Sounds like
a fruitcake, this Sarah.

316
00:22:08,894 --> 00:22:10,703
Veronica.
Her name's Veronica.

317
00:22:12,197 --> 00:22:15,406
What? I thought you said
the diary belonged to Sarah?

318
00:22:15,467 --> 00:22:17,310
Apparently, yes, the diary, yes,

319
00:22:17,369 --> 00:22:19,178
left to me by Sarah Ford.

320
00:22:19,237 --> 00:22:21,808
- Who is?
- Veronica's mother.

321
00:22:22,908 --> 00:22:25,946
So, you... you slept with Veronica
or you slept with Sarah?

322
00:22:26,712 --> 00:22:29,818
Strictly speaking, neither.
Sadly.

323
00:22:31,183 --> 00:22:33,356
Veronica and I were together.

324
00:22:34,686 --> 00:22:36,097
Boyfriend and girlfriend.

325
00:22:36,154 --> 00:22:38,430
Exactly, yes.
Kind-kind of an item, yes.

326
00:22:39,658 --> 00:22:41,729
- But that...
- And that's how you know Sarah.

327
00:22:43,995 --> 00:22:46,134
- Yes.
- Right.

328
00:22:47,699 --> 00:22:48,973
So we're getting somewhere.

329
00:22:49,668 --> 00:22:51,705
(horn honking)

330
00:23:03,048 --> 00:23:04,891
Looks like he's planning to move in.

331
00:23:06,385 --> 00:23:07,625
You look nervous.

332
00:23:08,820 --> 00:23:10,197
Tony, this is my father.

333
00:23:11,156 --> 00:23:12,863
- Tony.
- David.

334
00:23:14,126 --> 00:23:16,572
We've heard all about you, Tony.
Come on.

335
00:23:16,628 --> 00:23:18,471
Let's get you two lovebirds home.

336
00:23:28,807 --> 00:23:30,184
(horn honks)

337
00:23:41,987 --> 00:23:43,330
Ta-da!

338
00:23:43,388 --> 00:23:45,129
Oh, um...

339
00:23:45,190 --> 00:23:48,137
you can pee into the basin at night,
if you wish.

340
00:23:48,193 --> 00:23:50,070
(chuckles)

341
00:24:03,742 --> 00:24:05,744
(woman singing indistinctly)

342
00:24:15,787 --> 00:24:16,857
(man clears throat)

343
00:24:23,728 --> 00:24:25,036
Not bad, eh?

344
00:24:26,665 --> 00:24:28,008
Jack.

345
00:24:29,100 --> 00:24:30,670
I'm the big brother.

346
00:24:30,735 --> 00:24:32,180
Tony.

347
00:24:32,237 --> 00:24:35,775
- We've heard all about you, Tony.
- Oh? (Laughs)

348
00:24:35,841 --> 00:24:38,515
How do you like your lamb, Tony?

349
00:24:38,577 --> 00:24:40,079
Sorry?

350
00:24:40,712 --> 00:24:43,283
- We're having lamb this evening.
- (both chuckle)

351
00:24:43,348 --> 00:24:45,794
Oh. I see.

352
00:24:46,384 --> 00:24:48,125
Excellent.

353
00:24:49,888 --> 00:24:54,394
I'm, uh, I'm partial to a bit
of rare meat myself.

354
00:25:01,466 --> 00:25:02,877
I'll let you get settled.

355
00:25:07,072 --> 00:25:08,244
(door closes)

356
00:25:16,548 --> 00:25:18,027
(chuckles)

357
00:25:28,627 --> 00:25:30,834
Here, Tony,
have some roast potatoes.

358
00:25:30,896 --> 00:25:32,136
Thank you.

359
00:25:33,865 --> 00:25:35,811
Thank you, Mrs. Ford,
it all looks lovely.

360
00:25:35,867 --> 00:25:38,108
Hear, hear.
Motion seconded.

361
00:25:38,169 --> 00:25:39,614
Jack:
And me, please, Mother.

362
00:25:41,106 --> 00:25:42,380
Thank you.

363
00:25:43,074 --> 00:25:45,520
- How many?
- One more, please.

364
00:25:46,978 --> 00:25:48,184
Sarah:
Pass it down.

365
00:25:49,781 --> 00:25:51,158
Do start.

366
00:25:59,858 --> 00:26:03,635
Uh, a friend of mine's
at Cambridge, as it happens.

367
00:26:03,695 --> 00:26:05,538
Uh, Adrian Finn?

368
00:26:06,831 --> 00:26:10,335
- Should I know him?
- Uh, he's studying philosophy.

369
00:26:11,536 --> 00:26:13,482
My deepest sympathies.

370
00:26:13,538 --> 00:26:14,846
(laughter)

371
00:26:14,906 --> 00:26:16,749
(kicks under table)

372
00:26:16,808 --> 00:26:20,381
Sarah: And what about you, Tony?
You haven't told us what your subject is.

373
00:26:21,179 --> 00:26:23,216
English literature.

374
00:26:23,281 --> 00:26:25,426
Sarah: And what do you hope to do
with an undergraduate degree

375
00:26:25,450 --> 00:26:26,861
in English literature?

376
00:26:28,453 --> 00:26:30,694
Well, um...

377
00:26:30,755 --> 00:26:32,325
I-I hope to write.

378
00:26:32,390 --> 00:26:34,233
- Write?
- Yes.

379
00:26:35,327 --> 00:26:37,864
Um, poems. Poetry.

380
00:26:39,097 --> 00:26:41,236
A Poet?

381
00:26:49,474 --> 00:26:52,284
And who's your favorite poet?

382
00:26:52,344 --> 00:26:53,982
Mum.

383
00:26:54,045 --> 00:26:56,821
- Dylan Thomas.
- David: Ah, yes, yes.

384
00:26:56,881 --> 00:26:59,054
The gloomy Welshman.

385
00:26:59,117 --> 00:27:01,620
Jack:
“And the winds did bloom,

386
00:27:01,686 --> 00:27:04,064
and the brides in the wooed field

387
00:27:04,122 --> 00:27:07,103
did sew the coming
summer frost."

388
00:27:07,158 --> 00:27:09,900
David:
Ah, bravo, Jack.

389
00:27:11,162 --> 00:27:13,199
See what I have to
put up with, Tony?

390
00:27:16,334 --> 00:27:18,814
I'm partial to
a little Larkin myself.

391
00:27:18,870 --> 00:27:20,611
Oh, yes.

392
00:27:20,672 --> 00:27:22,674
He's wonderful, also.

393
00:27:25,276 --> 00:27:29,122
"I work all day,
and get half drunk at night.

394
00:27:32,183 --> 00:27:36,154
Waking at four to soundless dark...

395
00:27:37,288 --> 00:27:39,063
I stare.

396
00:27:40,558 --> 00:27:44,597
In time,
the curtain-edges will go bright."

397
00:27:47,332 --> 00:27:48,606
(chuckles awkwardly)

398
00:28:02,947 --> 00:28:04,722
Jack: Hear, hear.

399
00:28:04,783 --> 00:28:06,626
(chuckles bashfully)

400
00:28:25,437 --> 00:28:27,576
So...
(sighs)

401
00:28:28,673 --> 00:28:30,550
Good night, then.

402
00:28:32,544 --> 00:28:34,717
(whispers) Wait, I didn't
say anything embarrassing

403
00:28:34,779 --> 00:28:36,087
at dinner, did I?

404
00:28:37,549 --> 00:28:39,290
(Whispers)
Why are you whispering?

405
00:28:39,350 --> 00:28:40,761
(whispers)
I don't know.

406
00:28:40,819 --> 00:28:42,196
(normal voice)
Sorry.

407
00:28:53,865 --> 00:28:57,312
(whispers) I hope you sleep
the sleep of the wicked.

408
00:29:08,246 --> 00:29:11,523
(groaning)

409
00:29:16,321 --> 00:29:18,096
It's important you
understand the scale

410
00:29:18,156 --> 00:29:20,500
of sexual frustration
of my younger self.

411
00:29:21,326 --> 00:29:24,307
For God's sake.
You poor thing.

412
00:29:31,870 --> 00:29:34,146
You sure there isn't
some un-doused fire

413
00:29:34,205 --> 00:29:35,912
in your breast, Mr. Webster?

414
00:29:35,974 --> 00:29:37,419
Quite sure.

415
00:29:38,576 --> 00:29:42,786
So if... let's presume,
still unmarried fruitcake

416
00:29:42,847 --> 00:29:45,259
walked into this restaurant now

417
00:29:45,316 --> 00:29:48,092
and sat in that table...

418
00:29:49,087 --> 00:29:51,693
how would the long-divorced
Mr. Anthony Webster react?

419
00:29:51,756 --> 00:29:54,999
I don't think I'd be
especially pleased to see her.

420
00:29:56,261 --> 00:29:59,731
So you wouldn't start rolling up
your sleeves and turning over your watch?

421
00:29:59,798 --> 00:30:02,369
God.
I wish I'd never told you that.

422
00:30:03,434 --> 00:30:05,812
Can we have another...
More coffee?

423
00:30:12,143 --> 00:30:14,714
Come on,
let's hear the rest of it.

424
00:30:16,247 --> 00:30:17,920
- Sarah: Morning.
- (metal clatters)

425
00:30:18,883 --> 00:30:22,956
- You looking for something?
- (chuckles) No, I was just looking.

426
00:30:25,523 --> 00:30:27,799
The others have gone for a walk.

427
00:30:27,859 --> 00:30:29,896
Veronica said
you'd prefer a lie-in,

428
00:30:29,961 --> 00:30:32,339
so we opted not to disturb you.

429
00:30:34,966 --> 00:30:36,343
You hungry?

430
00:30:37,769 --> 00:30:38,770
Uh, yes.

431
00:30:42,273 --> 00:30:43,775
Have a seat.
(chuckles)

432
00:30:49,647 --> 00:30:51,923
(Sarah humming)

433
00:31:11,069 --> 00:31:14,482
You won't let Veronica get away
with too much, will you?

434
00:31:16,674 --> 00:31:17,675
Sorry?

435
00:31:19,677 --> 00:31:21,418
Don't let her get away
with too much.

436
00:31:25,717 --> 00:31:28,425
Sorry, I'm not quite sure
I follow your meaning.

437
00:31:29,187 --> 00:31:31,064
Oh! Damn it!

438
00:31:32,423 --> 00:31:34,425
(hissing)

439
00:31:35,260 --> 00:31:37,001
Whoops.
(laughs)

440
00:31:38,563 --> 00:31:39,974
Sorry.

441
00:31:41,366 --> 00:31:44,779
I'm normally very good at eggs.
(chuckles)

442
00:31:45,770 --> 00:31:48,114
- Tony, let me give you a hand.
- Thank you.

443
00:31:48,172 --> 00:31:50,174
(David humming)

444
00:31:52,810 --> 00:31:54,983
Well, Jack.

445
00:31:57,048 --> 00:31:58,652
He'll do, I suppose.

446
00:31:58,716 --> 00:32:00,457
(all laughing)

447
00:32:01,786 --> 00:32:04,494
Thanks for staying
the weekend, Tony.

448
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:06,865
Thank you, Mrs. Ford.

449
00:32:10,929 --> 00:32:11,930
(engine starts)

450
00:32:19,437 --> 00:32:22,884
(David humming)

451
00:32:29,514 --> 00:32:31,425
I like your mum.

452
00:32:31,482 --> 00:32:34,861
(David laughs)
Sounds like you've got a rival, Vron.

453
00:32:35,753 --> 00:32:37,993
Come to think of it,
sounds like you're not the only one.

454
00:32:39,557 --> 00:32:41,537
Excuse me, I'm still speaking.

455
00:32:41,592 --> 00:32:43,538
You don't say.

456
00:32:43,594 --> 00:32:45,369
Something is clearly going on.

457
00:32:45,430 --> 00:32:47,205
Someone you knew long ago

458
00:32:47,265 --> 00:32:50,144
has left you something or other.

459
00:32:50,201 --> 00:32:53,774
Exactly. Which has been
unduly withheld from me

460
00:32:53,838 --> 00:32:55,579
and to which
I am legally entitled.

461
00:32:55,640 --> 00:32:59,452
Well, you could fight it,
or you can just let it go.

462
00:33:00,578 --> 00:33:03,184
Cash the check,
take me on a budget holiday.

463
00:33:03,982 --> 00:33:06,826
250 each,
get us to the Channel Islands.

464
00:33:06,884 --> 00:33:09,660
- Listen, the point I...
- Something is certainly going on.

465
00:33:11,356 --> 00:33:14,337
So just call me when you
really want to talk about it.

466
00:33:22,900 --> 00:33:25,938
Oh, and the foot's much better,
thanks for asking.

467
00:33:26,004 --> 00:33:28,610
How is it, the foot?

468
00:33:28,673 --> 00:33:31,586
(door opens, closes)

469
00:33:33,644 --> 00:33:35,646
(music playing)

470
00:33:46,357 --> 00:33:49,463
(alarm clock ringing)

471
00:34:01,139 --> 00:34:03,141
(car horn honks)

472
00:34:29,567 --> 00:34:31,979
Woman:
So, I passed on your letters,

473
00:34:32,036 --> 00:34:34,277
all 13 of them, to Miss Ford.

474
00:34:34,338 --> 00:34:37,342
- And?
- While Miss Ford is still not ready

475
00:34:37,408 --> 00:34:39,012
to part with the diary.

476
00:34:39,077 --> 00:34:41,387
I can tell you that the diary,
it seems,

477
00:34:41,446 --> 00:34:43,187
belonged to a Mr. Adrian Finn.

478
00:34:45,083 --> 00:34:46,391
I see.

479
00:34:46,451 --> 00:34:49,830
Now, I've raised your concern
in terms of if or when

480
00:34:49,887 --> 00:34:52,390
you might be able to receive
Mr. Finn's diary.

481
00:34:52,457 --> 00:34:53,834
Let me get this straight.

482
00:34:53,891 --> 00:34:57,134
She should have handed
the diary over to you.

483
00:34:57,195 --> 00:34:58,538
She hasn't.

484
00:34:58,596 --> 00:35:00,371
You've asked for it,

485
00:35:00,431 --> 00:35:02,536
but she's refusing to give it up.

486
00:35:02,600 --> 00:35:05,012
Yes, that's-that's certainly
how things stand at present.

487
00:35:10,908 --> 00:35:14,219
In my experience,
Mr. Webster,

488
00:35:14,278 --> 00:35:17,725
people often like to take some time out
following a bereavement.

489
00:35:17,782 --> 00:35:19,762
Don't you think?

490
00:35:19,817 --> 00:35:22,297
That's as may be.

491
00:35:22,353 --> 00:35:24,856
But I want to be quite sure

492
00:35:24,922 --> 00:35:29,393
that you are clear that
that diary belongs to me.

493
00:35:32,430 --> 00:35:33,670
- (brakes squeal)
- (horn honks)

494
00:35:39,837 --> 00:35:41,077
(car lock beeps)

495
00:35:44,642 --> 00:35:46,417
Hello.

496
00:35:46,477 --> 00:35:49,321
Andrew, this is Tony,
my ex-husband.

497
00:35:49,380 --> 00:35:50,415
Ah.

498
00:35:50,481 --> 00:35:52,483
How are you doing, Tony?
All right?

499
00:35:52,550 --> 00:35:55,258
- Hi.
- We work together.

500
00:35:55,319 --> 00:35:57,731
Can we talk?
It's important.

501
00:35:59,357 --> 00:36:02,167
Well, I'll leave you to it, then.

502
00:36:02,226 --> 00:36:03,899
Good to meet you, Tony.

503
00:36:03,961 --> 00:36:05,065
I'll see you Monday.

504
00:36:09,667 --> 00:36:12,978
This is not on, Tony, coming around
without being asked, sorry.

505
00:36:13,037 --> 00:36:16,211
You told me to call when I was ready
to tell you what was going on.

506
00:36:18,910 --> 00:36:20,514
(muffled)
You gonna let me in?

507
00:36:20,578 --> 00:36:22,580
Headmaster:
From summer to autumn.

508
00:36:22,647 --> 00:36:24,957
So, too, do we think ahead...

509
00:36:25,016 --> 00:36:26,723
(chuckles)
Rather him than us.

510
00:36:26,784 --> 00:36:29,458
To what we may achieve together.

511
00:36:30,955 --> 00:36:33,162
(boys laughing)

512
00:36:40,665 --> 00:36:41,837
